e, Armand, Laurent, Leonce, Marcel, Yves, Clovis, Fernand, Gilberte, Janvier, Jean Claude.","Scottish, English, North German, French, Walloon, Catalan, and West Indian (mainly Haiti): from a personal name composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘renown’ +<i>gār</i>, <i>gēr</i> ‘spear, lance’, which was introduced into England by the Normans in the form <i>Rog(i)er</i> and was reinforced by the Old Norse cognate <i>Hróthgeirr</i>.","History: Gabriel Roger from Sainte-Verge in Deux-Sèvres, France, married Marie (de) Lacour in Quebec City, QC, in 1669. — This surname is listed in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors and also in the similar register of the Huguenot Society of South Carolina."]},{"name":"Rodgers","meanings":["English and Irish: variant of   Rogers  ."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir John Rogers was born in 1411, in Bryanston, Dorset, England, United Kingdom, his father, Sir John FitzRogers, was 25 and his mother, Agnes Mordaunt, was 21. He had at least 1 son with Anne Echingham. In 1464, his occupation is listed as minister of parliament and sheriff  in Berkshire, England. He died on 4 August 1450, in his hometown, at the age of 39."},"et":{"1411 Ancestory.com–4 August 1450":"1411–4. august 1450","1405–1500":"1405–1500","1408–1471":"1408–1471","1411–1450":"1411–1450","1429–1498":"1429–1498","1448–1507":"1448–1507","1386–1441":"1386–1441","1390–1441":"1390–1441","6 October 1441":"6. oktoober 1441","4 October 1441":"4. oktoober 1441","1450":"1450","1471":"1471","1411 Ancestory.com":"1411","1390":"1390","1 March 1448":"1. märts 1448","4 August 1450":"4. august 1450","1448":"1448","1500":"1500","1411":"1411","1498":"1498","1441":"1441","1386":"1386","1507":"1507","1408":"1408","1429":"1429","1406":"1406